**Further reading.** The original GRACE mission overview is {cite}`tapley2004`. The first GRACE-based acceleration of Greenland mass loss is {cite}`velicogna2006`. For the IMBIE reconciliation, see [TODO-CITE: IMBIE team Antarctica 2018] and [TODO-CITE: IMBIE team Greenland 2020]. For a detailed treatment of mascon processing choices and their impact on regional trend estimates, see [TODO-CITE: Watkins mascon processing JPL 2015].

Gravity occupies a peculiar position among the observing methods in this part. Its raw observable — the changing distance between two refrigerator-sized satellites 220 km apart, measured to the width of a red blood cell — is so far from the scientific quantity of interest that you cannot retrace the processing without specialised infrastructure. Yet the quantity it delivers — mass in gigatonnes — is arguably the most direct measurement glaciology possesses. No density assumption, no velocity-thickness product, no atmospheric correction for the target variable itself. The honesty required of a GRACE user is not about opening every raw file; it is about being explicit on three fronts: the GIA correction and its range of published values, the leakage correction and what it assumes about the spatial distribution of mass change, and the gap between missions and what you are and are not willing to claim about what happened in it. This lab has given you the tools to address all three in your own work.</cell id="synthesis-md">
